<dl id="n10053a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10053a">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10053a"> 53(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 24 o&apos;clock <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10053a"><li>FW 87.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n10053a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n10053a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10053a">MS BL 47472-267</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:099 <a name="dd5" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd5.htm#n10053a">Draft: I.4&sect;1.5</a>/2.5</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Le gouvernement italien, par un d&eacute;cret royal (en date du 10 ao&ucirc;t 1893), qui prescrit la nouvelle heure, consacre une seconde innovation emprunt&eacute;e &agrave; l&apos;Am&eacute;rique du Nord et qu&apos;il importe de signaler, puisque des hommes, soi-disant &ldquo;dans le train&rdquo;. pr&eacute;disent que peu &agrave; peu, elle deviendra la r&egrave;gle exclusive pour toute l&apos;Europe. Il s&apos;agit de compter les heures du jour sans interruption de minuit &agrave; minuit, sans distinction des heures du matin, et des heures du soir qui compliquent tant les horaires actuels. On dira: <mark>13 heures au lieu de 1 heure du soir. &hellip; 23 -- -- 11 <font color="green">[The Italian government, by a royal decree (dated August 10, 1893), which prescribed the new system of time, authorised a second innovation, borrowed from North America, which it is important to mention because men who are supposedly &ldquo;in the know&rdquo; predict that it will gradually become the general rule throughout Europe. It consists of counting the hours of the day from midnight to midnight without interruption and without differentiating morning hours from evening hours, something which so greatly complicates current schedules: One will say: 13 hours instead of 1 p.m. &hellip; 23 -- 11]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 141-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
